    <title>Combined summary - BIP proposal: Timelocked address fidelity bond for BIP39 seeds</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T20:14:03.101249+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-May/020481.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In various conversations and exchanges, the concept of fidelity bonds has been explored in relation to Joinmarket and Teleport systems. Fidelity bonds are used to protect against sybil attacks by making cryptographic identity expensive to obtain. The sacrifice made by a user committing to Joinmarket with FB1 is discussed, as well as the benefits obtained from using FB1 in both Joinmarket and Teleport. While there is some concern about not knowing if FB1 is being used elsewhere, it is argued that the value of the sacrifice remains the same regardless of how many applications it is used for. However, sharing coins between the two systems could increase the risk of partial-protocol attacks and reduce privacy. A BIP proposes a method for storing timelocked address fidelity bonds in BIP39 phrases and signing fidelity bond certificates. The potential benefits and drawbacks of renting out fidelity bonds are also discussed, with concerns about privacy implications and surveillance. There is speculation about the possibility of offering fidelity bonds for lease without caring about the actual applications they are used for. The equation Y+Z &gt; X is used to explain why most fidelity bond owners are expected to use their bonds with both Joinmarket and Teleport. An attacker who successfully does a sybil attack against Joinmarket can also do a successful sybil attack against Teleport with little added cost. Therefore, both markets form a single fidelity bond ecosystem.Other discussions explore the concept of using someone else's proof of burn (PoB) to prove an expense, and the defiads network, where a UTXO can host only one advertisement at any one time. Each advertisement would have a specific application ID, and a UTXO could only be used for one application at a time. This would be equivalent to domain separation tags. The BIP contains a definition of address derivation and how to sign fidelity bond certificates. The abstract points out that the BIP contains both, but the second area is much more tricky.The conversation between two individuals, E and ZmnSCPxj, revolves around lending and borrowing, where the lender provides the use of the principal and gets paid interest in return, while the borrower uses the principal to generate income from producing goods and selling them. The discussion also touches on the use of fidelity bonds to back trust assertions in scenarios where funds are not being transferred. The reuse of fidelity bonds in different applications is discussed, with concerns raised about potential privacy trade-offs. The conversation also covers defiads and domain separation tags. The scope of a BIP containing both the definition of address derivation and how to sign fidelity bond certificates is questioned. The possibility of renting out fidelity bonds for generating yield is discussed, with concerns raised about fixed rent cost and the potential for surveillance. Chris Belcher proposes a solution to remove the intermediate certificate keypair and sign the endpoint directly to address privacy concerns. The email exchange also touches on the use of the same fidelity bond in JoinMarket and Teleport makers and the potential for abuse. Finally, the email discusses the possibility of renting a fidelity bond for different applications using a pay-for-signature protocol now that Taproot is available.The discussion between Chris Belcher and ZmnSCPxj on the bitcoin-dev mailing list revolves around the use of fidelity bonds in Joinmarket and Teleport. They discuss the potential of using fidelity bonds for multiple applications, increasing their left-hand-side value while the right-hand-side value remains constant. However, there is a concern regarding assessing FB1 being used for other applications as well. The two also discuss the possibility of renting fidelity bonds for generating yield, which comes with the risk of a random income not covering the fixed rent cost. Chris proposes a solution to this issue by removing the intermediate certificate keypair and having the fidelity bond UTXO key sign the endpoint directly to eliminate the possibility of fidelity bonds in cold storage. The sender discusses the concept of lending, where the lender provides the use of the principal and gets paid interest in exchange. The borrower trades the principle with others, and at maturity, the coin is returned to the lender by covenant. While the lack of usability is a cost to the lender, it is not a benefit to the borrower. The discussion is about the net present value of the loan, and the sender believes that the net present value of the loan is zero.The BIP proposal defines a method for storing timelocked address fidelity bonds in BIP39 phrases and signing fidelity bond certificates. Fidelity bonds are used to resist sybil attacks in certain decentralized anonymous protocols, and they can be created by locking up bitcoins using the `OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY` opcode. By defining a common derivation scheme, users of wallet software can have a backup of their fidelity bonds by storing only the BIP39 seed phrase and a reference to this BIP.Chris Belcher, a Bitcoin privacy developer, discusses various ways to increase the privacy of coinjoin and coinswap transactions. He emphasizes the importance of maintaining the privacy of makers to</summary>
